<section id="section-1d">
<title> Average velocity 
</title>
<example id="example-43">
<para id="element-43"><term>Problem : </term> A particle moving in a straight line covers 1/3rd of the distance with a velocity 4 m/s. The remaining part of the linear distance is covered with velocities 2 m/s and 6 m/s for equal times. What is the average velocity during the total motion?
</para>
<para id="element-44"> <term>Solution : </term> The average velocity is ratio of displacement and time. In one dimensional unidirectional motion, distance and displacement are same. As such, average velocity is ratio of total distance and time. 
</para>

<para id="element-45">Let the total distance be “x”. Now, we need to find total time in order to find the average velocity. Let "
<m:math>
<m:msub>
<m:mi> t </m:mi>
<m:mn> 1 </m:mn>
</m:msub>
</m:math>
", "
